Neural Network MARS Applicated on simulated data¶

References :

Article [1] (English) : Adaptive splines-based logistic regression with a ReLU neural network, Marie Guyomard, Susana Barbosa, Lionel Fillatre, JOBIM, 2022. ⟨hal-03778323⟩

Article [2] (French) : Régression logistique à base de splines adaptatives avec un réseau de neurones ReLU, Marie Guyomard, Susana Barbosa, Lionel Fillatre, GRETZSI, 2022. ⟨hal-03778328⟩

NN-MARS Model¶

The above algorithm is available here for binary classification problems.

Let suppose we have $N$ independant and identically distributed pairs $\{x^{(i)}, y^{(i)}\}_{i=1}^{N}$. We consider the following neural network :

$$f(x) = \hat{\mathbb{P}}\left(Y=1|X\right) = \sigma(\psi_X(\theta)).$$

with

$$\sigma = \frac{1}{1+\exp(-X)} $$

and $$\psi_X(\theta) = \beta_0 + \beta \phi\left(\bar{W}X^T+b\right).$$

such as

$\phi(X) = \text{ReLU}(X) = \max\{0,X\} \\ X \in\mathbb{R}^{N \times d} \\ b = [b_{11}, b_{12}, \dots, b_{d1}, b_{d2}]^T \in \mathbb{R}^{2d} \\ \beta = [\beta_{11}, \beta_{12}, \dots, \beta_{d1}, \beta_{d2}] \in \mathbb{R}^{2d} \\ \bar{W} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 1 & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & -1 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & \dots & 0 \\ \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^{2d \times d} \\ \theta = [\beta_0, \beta, b^T]^T = [\beta_0, \beta_1, \dots, \beta_d, b_1, \dots, b_p]^T $

Remark : for binar categorical variable, only one node is created.

Simulated Data¶

We simulated $x \in \mathbb{R}^2$ data in order to visualize the estimated decision boundaries.

We seek to predict the probability of developing a pathology as a function of cholesterol level ($X_1$) and weight ($X_2$). Both variables are simulated according to normal distributions, in order to consider normalized data. The labels were constructed as follow :

  • When the cholesterol level is low, the patient is more protected against the disease ($\beta_{11} = -2$). On the other hand, when it is high, the patient is more at risk ($\beta_{12}=4$).
  • Being underweight or overweight increases the probability of developing the pathology (respectively $\beta_{21}=1.5$ and $\beta_{22}=3$).

Since in real applications the boundary is noisy, we define the labels using a Bernouilli distribution with the estimated probability of developing the disease as parameter.

In [3]:
np.random.seed(407)

# Features 
data = pd.DataFrame({'X1':np.random.randn(5000), 'X2':np.random.randn(5000)})

beta_0, beta_11, beta_12, beta_21, beta_22 = 0, -2, 4, 1.5, 3
t11, t12, t21, t22 = 0, 1, -1, 1

# Labels
label = []
for i in range(data.shape[0]):
    score_i=beta_0
    if data.loc[i, 'X1']<=t11:
        score_i += beta_12 * (t11-data.loc[i, 'X1'])
    if data.loc[i, 'X1']>=t12:
        score_i += beta_11 * (data.loc[i, 'X1']-t12)
    if data.loc[i, 'X2'] <= t21:
        score_i += beta_21 * (t21-data.loc[i, 'X2'])
    if data.loc[i, 'X2'] >= t22:
        score_i += beta_22 * (data.loc[i, 'X2']-t22)
   
    proba_i = 1/(1+math.exp(score_i))
    label.append(np.random.binomial(n = 1, p = proba_i, size = 1)[0])
        
data['label']=label
X = data[['X1', 'X2']]

In [7]:
index_1 = random.sample(np.where(pd.DataFrame(label)==0)[0].tolist(), 1000)
index_2 = random.sample(np.where(pd.DataFrame(label)==1)[0].tolist(), 1000)

data_balanced = data.iloc[index_1+index_2,:]
data_balanced = data_balanced.reset_index()
data_balanced.drop(['index'], axis='columns', inplace=True)

X_balanced = data_balanced[['X1', 'X2']]

Plot estimated splines¶

We here plot the estimated splines by NN-MARS. To do so, we generate a sequence of data and apply the best estimated NN-MARS (the one who maximises the AUC on the test sample).

In [17]:
NNMARS_plot_splines(X_balanced, models_fold[np.argmax(res_iter['auc_test'])], figsize=(5,5), Save_Fig=False, path=[])

Plot boundary¶

We here plot the estimated boundary on the training set. To do so, we plot the simulated data. Then we generate a meshgrid and apply the best estimated NN-MARS (the one who maximises the AUC on the test sample). We then add on the plot, the boundaries estimated by the first layer (in black) and the final decision rule (in red).

Remarks : this method works for binary classification problem with only 2 features.

This method was inspired by the work of Randall Balestriero concerning the vizualisation of splines estimated in deep networks provided here : https://github.com/RandallBalestriero/spline-DN-visualization

Application to imbalanced dataset¶

For this example, we use the reweighted binary cross entropy loss : $$L_{w} = \prod_{i=1}^{N} \hat{\mathbb{P}}\left(Y_i=1|X_i\right)^{w_1y_i} \times \left(1 - \hat{\mathbb{P}}\left(Y_i=1|X_i\right)\right)^{w_2(1-y_i)}.$$

with

$$w_k = \frac{N}{\sum_{i=1}^N \mathbb{1}_{\{Y_i=k\}}}.$$
